WEBVTT

00:00.657 --> 00:04.024
<i>[ Woman Narrating ]</i>
<i>Theorizing that one could time travel</i>
<i>within his own lifetime,</i>

00:04.094 --> 00:07.621
<i>Dr. Sam Beckett led an elite group</i>
<i>of scientists into the desert...</i>

00:07.697 --> 00:11.827
<i>to develop a top secret project</i>
<i>known as Quantum Leap.</i>

00:11.901 --> 00:14.563
<i>Pressured to prove his theories</i>
<i>or lose funding,</i>

00:14.637 --> 00:18.300
<i>Dr. Beckett prematurely stepped</i>
<i>into the project accelerator...</i>

00:18.374 --> 00:20.706
<i>and vanished.</i>

00:26.716 --> 00:29.082
<i>He awoke to find himself in the past,</i>

00:29.152 --> 00:34.419
<i>suffering from partial amnesia</i>
<i>and facing a mirror image</i>
<i>that was not his own.</i>

00:34.491 --> 00:37.756
<i>Fortunately, contact with</i>
<i>his own time was maintained...</i>

00:37.827 --> 00:40.853
<i>through brain wave transmissions</i>
<i>with Al, the project observer,</i>

00:40.930 --> 00:45.663
<i>who appeared in the form of a hologram</i>
<i>that only Dr. Beckett can see and hear.</i>

00:45.735 --> 00:48.135
<i>Trapped in the past,</i>
<i>Dr. Beckett finds himself...</i>

00:48.204 --> 00:50.365
<i>leaping from life to life,</i>

00:50.440 --> 00:52.135
<i>putting things right</i>
<i>that once went wrong...</i>

00:52.208 --> 00:57.407
<i>and hoping each time that</i>
<i>his next leap will be the leap home.</i>

01:05.555 --> 01:08.319
- [ Groans ]
- <i>Lesson number one:¡</i>

01:08.391 --> 01:11.417
It never pays to get smart with me!

01:13.329 --> 01:15.627
[ Groans ]

01:17.000 --> 01:23.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:24.774 --> 01:27.299
Hazlitt!

01:27.377 --> 01:29.038
Ohh.

01:29.112 --> 01:32.912
Almost had you there, Sheriff.
Well, almost doesn't count!

01:46.596 --> 01:50.862
He slipped.
Looks like you slipped too.

01:59.342 --> 02:01.276
[ Groans ]

02:01.344 --> 02:03.278
<i>[ Door Closes ]</i>

02:05.648 --> 02:07.639
<i>[ Coughs ]</i>

02:31.941 --> 02:34.933
Oh, boy. I'm an Indian.

02:35.011 --> 02:37.775
<i>Could be worse.</i>

02:37.847 --> 02:40.338
You could be a white man, eh?

04:07.370 --> 04:10.635
<i>[ Sam Narrating ]</i>
<i>Apoet once said,</i>
<i>''Stone walls do not a prison make,</i>

04:10.707 --> 04:12.800
<i>nor iron bars a cage. ''</i>

04:12.875 --> 04:15.639
<i>But if this wasn't a cage,</i>
<i>it was a pretty good imitation of one.</i>

04:15.712 --> 04:18.146
I, uh,

04:19.482 --> 04:21.973
can't wait to get out of here.

04:23.219 --> 04:25.653
That may be a while.

04:25.722 --> 04:27.815
People around here...

04:27.890 --> 04:32.259
have peculiar ideas
about auto theft.

04:32.328 --> 04:36.594
I stole a car?
Like a pinto I had once.

04:36.666 --> 04:38.600
He was a brave pony.

04:38.668 --> 04:41.102
His name was Windwalker.

04:42.171 --> 04:45.663
-<i>[ Sam ] I stole a truck.</i>
- You borrowed it.

04:45.742 --> 04:48.176
I just got in.

04:48.244 --> 04:51.008
It's not like we were going to
keep it forever.

04:51.080 --> 04:54.174
That would be theft.
A lot of people
can't tell the difference...

04:54.250 --> 04:56.184
between borrowing and stealing.
Aah!

04:56.252 --> 04:58.186
Primitive cultures.

04:59.355 --> 05:01.289
Think you can pull one of these out?

05:01.357 --> 05:04.019
We can't break out of here.
I's against the law.

05:04.093 --> 05:08.189
Do you want to spend
the next 1 0 years in jail?

05:08.264 --> 05:11.529
Eating food off trays
like in the nursing home?

05:11.601 --> 05:14.229
No.
Well,

05:14.303 --> 05:16.237
then get us out of here.

05:19.308 --> 05:22.038
How?

05:22.111 --> 05:25.842
You're the big city man.
You figure it out.

05:30.787 --> 05:33.984
<i>[ Rooster Crowing ]</i>

05:34.057 --> 05:37.925
<i>(music) [ Man Chanting In Foreign Language ]</i>

05:42.298 --> 05:45.893
(music) [ Chanting Continues ]

05:47.804 --> 05:50.637
Where's George?

05:50.706 --> 05:52.731
- Gone.
- How?

05:52.809 --> 05:55.835
I turned him into a raven.

05:55.912 --> 05:58.642
He flew away.

05:58.714 --> 06:02.912
- Why didn't you go with him?
- I can only turn into a wolf.

06:02.985 --> 06:04.953
I'm too big for the bars.

06:07.256 --> 06:09.190
You stay where you are.

06:11.427 --> 06:14.453
(music) [ Resumes Chanting ]

06:18.101 --> 06:20.194
- Yaah!
- [ Groans ]

06:24.273 --> 06:26.207
He's out.

06:29.612 --> 06:32.638
Lesson number two--
Don't mess with Indians.

06:32.715 --> 06:34.649
Yeah.

06:36.552 --> 06:38.543
You call me, Sheriff?
[ Groans ]

06:43.593 --> 06:45.618
<i>Come on!</i>

06:45.695 --> 06:49.062
Did you ever notice
he looks like a sheep?

06:49.132 --> 06:51.225
Come on.

06:53.870 --> 06:55.804
Good morning.

06:55.872 --> 06:57.806
Get in the truck!
Okay.

07:03.312 --> 07:06.338
Damn! I gotta go get the keys.
[ Exhales ]

07:06.415 --> 07:08.940
Just hot-wire it
like you did before.

07:09.952 --> 07:12.284
<i>[ Starter Grinding ]</i>

07:12.355 --> 07:15.381
<i>[ Grinding Continues ]</i>
Hey! Hey! Stop him!

07:15.458 --> 07:18.859
[ Engine Starts ]
Forward, ho!

07:18.928 --> 07:20.862
They're escaping! Stop 'em!

07:27.904 --> 07:31.203
<i>[ Hazlitt ]</i>
<i>Yeah, I think my nose is broken.</i>
<i>[ Sheriff] Probably an improvement.</i>

07:31.274 --> 07:33.367
I just hope Lucille
still likes my face this way.

07:33.442 --> 07:35.842
Will you stop whining
about your nose
and get on the radio.

07:35.912 --> 07:38.346
I want those Indians stopped.
Okay. Okay, Sheriff.

07:41.317 --> 07:44.912
<i>Hello, Billy?</i>
<i>Word has it</i>--

07:44.987 --> 07:47.979
<i>[ Continues, Indistinct ]</i>

07:48.057 --> 07:50.719
Oh, excuse me.
I'm looking for SheriffTaggart.

07:50.793 --> 07:52.954
You found him.

07:53.029 --> 07:54.963
I'm Suzanne Washakie.

07:55.031 --> 07:57.625
I understand you have
my grandfather and brother here.

07:57.700 --> 08:00.100
- Nope.
- I'm sorry?

08:00.169 --> 08:02.228
<i>They were. They escaped.</i>

08:02.305 --> 08:04.364
About 1 5 minutes ago.
<i>Oh, God!</i>

08:04.440 --> 08:07.204
My grandfather's a very sick man.

08:07.276 --> 08:09.210
He needs to get back
to the nursing home.

08:09.278 --> 08:13.009
Your grandfather and your brother
have stolen a pickup... twice,

08:13.082 --> 08:16.245
assaulted two sheriff's officers
and escaped from jail.

08:16.319 --> 08:18.947
Now, I hate to say it,
but when I find him,

08:19.021 --> 08:21.922
the last place he's gonna go
is to a nursin' home.

08:25.127 --> 08:29.029
Sheriff, I'd like to come with you.

08:29.098 --> 08:31.032
Sure.

08:34.370 --> 08:36.929
You're a sworn deputy
of the state of Nevada,
aren't ya?

08:37.006 --> 08:39.405
No.

08:39.475 --> 08:41.966
Then you can't come.
[ Chuckles ]

08:42.044 --> 08:44.911
[ Engine Starts ]

08:56.926 --> 08:59.417
<i>[ Sam Narrating ]</i>
<i>There's an old Indian expression</i>
<i>that says...</i>

08:59.495 --> 09:02.623
<i>you should neverjudge a man until</i>
<i>you've walked a mile in his moccasins.</i>

09:02.698 --> 09:05.394
<i>I guess that applies to situations too.</i>

09:05.468 --> 09:07.834
<i>But so far,</i>
<i>I didn't enjoy being on the run.</i>

09:10.773 --> 09:13.037
Nevada.

09:13.109 --> 09:17.068
(music) Where the wind goes whistling
down the plain

09:17.146 --> 09:19.080
(music) [ Humming ]

09:19.148 --> 09:21.082
That's Oklahoma.

09:22.218 --> 09:24.948
Pretty good though, eh?

09:25.021 --> 09:26.955
Pretty horrible.

09:27.023 --> 09:29.685
Hmm.

09:29.759 --> 09:33.217
[ Static ]

09:35.197 --> 09:39.998
Damn white men
can't make anything
but more white men.

09:40.069 --> 09:43.436
[ Chuckling ]

09:43.506 --> 09:47.033
[ Coughing ]

09:47.109 --> 09:50.135
[ Coughing Continues ]

09:53.883 --> 09:56.545
Keep going.
Let me take a look at you.

09:59.188 --> 10:02.680
Take a deep breath.
[ Wheezing ]

10:14.236 --> 10:16.295
You've got emphysema,
don't you?

10:16.372 --> 10:19.864
Huh.
I've gotta get you
to a hospital.

10:19.942 --> 10:23.207
Go on.
You're not going anywhere.
I gotta get you some oxygen.

10:25.214 --> 10:27.444
Take me home.

10:27.516 --> 10:29.643
Do you have oxygen there?

10:31.754 --> 10:33.915
Okay then.

10:33.989 --> 10:35.923
<i>[ Al ]</i>
<i>There's no oxygen there, Sam,</i>

10:35.991 --> 10:39.620
unless you count
what's floating around free
in the atmosphere.

10:39.695 --> 10:43.256
Where's the nearest hospital?
No hospital.

10:43.332 --> 10:45.391
[ Whirring ]
Uh, mmm.

10:45.468 --> 10:48.130
It's about 50 miles
behind you.

10:49.705 --> 10:51.696
[ Sighs ]

10:53.709 --> 10:55.802
Wait! Wait!
You can't run away.

10:55.878 --> 10:59.075
<i>I'm not runnin'away.</i>
<i>I've gotta water the plants.</i>

10:59.148 --> 11:01.548
That truck is hard
on my kidneys.

11:01.617 --> 11:03.551
[ Sam ]
Oh.

11:05.154 --> 11:07.122
What's goin' on here, Al?

11:07.189 --> 11:09.248
- Well, let's see.
- [ Whirring ]

11:09.325 --> 11:12.260
Your name is George Washakie,

11:12.328 --> 11:15.991
25 years old,
grandson ofJoseph Washakie,

11:16.065 --> 11:17.999
who's a full-blooded
Shoshone Indian.

11:18.067 --> 11:21.594
He's 7 1 or 72--
Uh, 72 years old or so.

11:21.670 --> 11:24.161
I don't know.
His birth date is--
is kind of hazy.

11:24.240 --> 11:26.606
You haven't seen him
since you were 1 4,

11:26.675 --> 11:28.700
which happened
to be yesterday...

11:28.778 --> 11:30.769
when you helped him escape
from his nursing home.

11:30.846 --> 11:33.337
In a stolen truck.
Yeah.

11:33.416 --> 11:37.750
Uh, the nursing home, by the way--
that's where your sister Suzanne
put him until you arrived--

11:37.820 --> 11:40.254
and she's a schoolteacher.

11:40.322 --> 11:43.985
Now, we are in--
Nevada.

11:45.528 --> 11:48.497
Uh, and the year is--
1 97 0.

11:50.666 --> 11:53.430
License tag.

11:55.271 --> 11:58.035
[ Beeping ]
The date is--

11:58.107 --> 11:59.972
Huh.

12:00.042 --> 12:02.670
[ Chuckling ]
November 22.

12:02.745 --> 12:05.339
Ziggy says you're here to--
<i>[ Whirring ]</i>

12:05.414 --> 12:07.473
I'm here to saveJoseph's life.

12:07.550 --> 12:09.609
No.

12:09.685 --> 12:13.644
No. You're here to help him die.

12:16.258 --> 12:20.695
Al, I'm a doctor--
Or I-- I used to be a doctor.
I can't help him die.

12:20.763 --> 12:24.028
Right now,
you're George Washakie,
his grandson.

12:24.099 --> 12:26.033
And you've taken him
from the nursing home,

12:26.101 --> 12:28.092
so he can go back to die
where he was born.

12:28.170 --> 12:30.934
Right. And along the way
we stole a pickup truck,

12:31.006 --> 12:32.997
we broke out of jail,
and I slugged the sheriff!.

12:33.075 --> 12:35.066
You did what you had to do.

12:35.144 --> 12:38.602
Sam, the state and your sister
won't let him go back
to the reservation.

12:38.681 --> 12:41.241
They say it's too dangerous.
They say the trip would kill him.

12:41.317 --> 12:45.014
Well, they're right.
Sam, he doesn't wanna spend
the last year of his life...

12:45.087 --> 12:48.386
confined to a nursing home
in a hospital bed,
lookin' like a pincushion.

12:48.457 --> 12:52.325
He'll be alive.
Maybe just being alive
isn't enough.

12:52.394 --> 12:55.659
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>A good life deserves a good death.</i>

12:58.400 --> 13:00.664
I think--

13:00.736 --> 13:03.705
I think I should take you back
and put you in the nursing home,

13:03.772 --> 13:06.502
so you can be with your family
and your friends.

13:06.575 --> 13:10.341
What family?
There's only you and Suzanne.

13:10.412 --> 13:12.346
And you moved away.

13:12.414 --> 13:14.974
What about your friends?

13:15.050 --> 13:18.383
My friends are here.

13:18.454 --> 13:20.388
The sun.

13:20.456 --> 13:22.924
The sky.

13:22.992 --> 13:25.187
The wind.

13:25.261 --> 13:27.195
And the earth.

13:29.431 --> 13:32.229
The shape you're in,
your friends could kill you.

13:32.301 --> 13:34.531
<i>[ Hawk Screeches ]</i>

13:34.603 --> 13:36.594
My brother the hawk.

13:36.672 --> 13:40.438
[ Screeches ]
<i>All its life it flies where it wants.</i>

13:42.211 --> 13:44.145
<i>Fights where it wants.</i>

13:44.213 --> 13:46.147
Loves where it wants.

13:47.650 --> 13:51.086
Now, when it's near death,

13:51.153 --> 13:54.554
do you think it wants
to be put in a cage?

13:58.861 --> 14:02.490
You've been too long
among the white man, <i>Togo.</i>

14:08.137 --> 14:11.538
''Togo.''
That's Shoshone for grandson.

14:12.608 --> 14:16.408
To you, he's ''Kenu,''
grandfather.
[ Beeping, Whirring ]

14:16.478 --> 14:20.812
Al, I gotta take him back.
Sam, the Indian reservation...

14:20.883 --> 14:23.613
begins just over those mountains.

14:23.686 --> 14:25.620
The cops can't get in there.

14:25.688 --> 14:27.679
Al, he needs oxygen
and proper medical care!

14:27.756 --> 14:29.815
He's not gonna get it out there
playin' Geronimo.

14:29.892 --> 14:32.122
Sam, there is a man...

14:32.194 --> 14:34.128
with a badge following you.

14:34.196 --> 14:36.994
He doesn't like you.
He doesn't like Indians.

14:37.066 --> 14:40.695
IfJoseph goes back,
the last thing he's gonna get
is adequate medical care.

14:40.769 --> 14:43.294
In fact, you'll be lucky
if the both of you don't get shot!

14:49.044 --> 14:50.978
Joseph!

14:55.417 --> 14:57.351
Uh--

14:57.419 --> 15:00.479
<i>Kenu,</i>

15:00.556 --> 15:03.150
I'll take you to the reservation.

15:03.225 --> 15:06.786
But when we get there,
you've got to see a doctor.

15:06.862 --> 15:09.456
Okay.

15:09.531 --> 15:11.522
But I don't know
if I can help him.

15:17.640 --> 15:20.803
[ Taggart ]
Don't be such an idiot! They didn't
just turn into ravens and fly away!

15:20.876 --> 15:23.208
And tell Sheriff Baldwin
over at Buffalo Run...

15:23.278 --> 15:25.542
to send his boys down south
toward Yuma.

15:25.614 --> 15:28.515
And get the highway patrol
to station a--

15:28.584 --> 15:31.451
a unit near the Teton entrance
to Interstate 7 0.

15:31.520 --> 15:33.613
If they're not too busy
having donuts!

15:34.923 --> 15:38.017
He seems to get angry
at more than just Indians.

15:38.093 --> 15:40.857
Yeah, he's got a doghouse
built for everybody.

15:40.929 --> 15:43.864
<i>[Joseph Coughing ]</i>

15:43.932 --> 15:46.127
Pull over! Pull over!

15:47.536 --> 15:50.596
All right. All right. All right.
I'll pull over.
[ Coughs ]

15:50.673 --> 15:52.641
[ Coughing Continues ]

15:59.181 --> 16:02.378
<i>(music) [ Country, Distant ]</i>

16:13.595 --> 16:17.463
<i>[ Bells Jingling ]</i>
<i>(music) [ Continues ]</i>

16:17.533 --> 16:20.229
[ Snoring ]

16:20.302 --> 16:22.429
Oh, hey there.

16:22.504 --> 16:24.836
Hi.
What can I do for ya?

16:24.907 --> 16:26.932
Well--
Got any buffalo hides?

16:27.009 --> 16:28.943
Uh--

16:29.011 --> 16:31.275
You know,
we just sold our last one.

16:31.346 --> 16:34.747
We got some, uh,
real nice blankets
back here though.

16:34.817 --> 16:36.751
Uh.

16:44.226 --> 16:46.786
<i>(music) [ Continues ]</i>

16:58.941 --> 17:02.604
<i>[ Al ]</i>
<i>I remember a lot of stores like this</i>
<i>from when I was a kid.</i>

17:03.812 --> 17:05.746
So do I.

17:05.814 --> 17:09.306
My dad--
he used to buy me candy...

17:09.384 --> 17:11.477
just like this every time
we went into town.

17:11.553 --> 17:14.818
Mmm.
My favorite was red licorice.

17:14.890 --> 17:17.450
I used to get a long piece
of that.
I used to get two sticks...

17:17.526 --> 17:20.119
Shirley Mulcahey
would get at one end,
of cinnamon.

17:20.194 --> 17:22.185
and I would start
at the other end.

17:22.263 --> 17:24.493
And then--
And he would get two sticks--

17:24.566 --> 17:27.000
Of peppermint.

17:27.069 --> 17:29.936
Your father
loved sweets all his life.

17:31.006 --> 17:33.770
That's where you got
your taste for 'em, eh, <i>Togo?</i>

17:33.842 --> 17:36.310
[ Chuckles ]
Hey, you know, Sam,
it's weird,

17:36.378 --> 17:39.643
but George Washakie's father
died when he was 21 too.

17:39.715 --> 17:41.649
Just like--
Me?

17:41.717 --> 17:44.777
No, I'm talkin'
to another Indian.

17:46.989 --> 17:50.481
I always preferred
cinnamon myself.

17:50.559 --> 17:52.993
<i>Anything else?</i>

17:53.061 --> 17:55.621
How about a fat woman
and a narrow bed?

17:58.967 --> 18:04.303
- I'm gonna remember that one, Sam.
- Uh, that'll be 47.5 5.

18:04.373 --> 18:06.307
[ Sighs ]

18:15.551 --> 18:17.610
Ah--

18:17.686 --> 18:21.349
All right. Okay.
You-- You can have whatever you want.

18:21.423 --> 18:25.325
Oh, great, Sam!
Why don't you go for five felonies
while you're at it.

18:25.394 --> 18:27.624
No! Uh, we're not gonna rob you.

18:27.696 --> 18:32.497
I just-- I-- I want to trade you
the gun for the blankets.

18:33.769 --> 18:35.862
And the Winchester.

18:35.938 --> 18:38.634
<i>That old one on the wall.</i>

18:41.210 --> 18:43.508
<i>[ Al ]</i>
<i>Sam, I wonder if that one</i>
<i>can even shoot.</i>

18:45.180 --> 18:48.581
- And one more thing.
- What might that be?

18:56.959 --> 18:59.519
Okay now,
put the hose to your mouth...

18:59.595 --> 19:02.587
and take a little breath,
but not too much.

19:03.765 --> 19:06.734
What you're trying to do
is give yourself oxygen
without shutting down...

19:06.802 --> 19:09.293
your O2 respiration
trigger mechanism.

19:11.773 --> 19:14.003
Where'd you learn that, <i>Togo?</i>

19:15.844 --> 19:17.778
Uh--

19:17.846 --> 19:19.939
Uh-- Uh, TV.

19:20.015 --> 19:22.381
Oh, <i>Marcus Welby.</i>

19:22.451 --> 19:24.942
<i>Marcus Welby?</i>

19:26.321 --> 19:28.881
For you.

19:30.893 --> 19:34.454
You stole that.
You stole all that stuff.

19:34.529 --> 19:37.430
Your gun was worth much more
than he said.

19:38.734 --> 19:41.100
<i>He tried to cheat us.</i>

19:48.343 --> 19:51.642
- Gun wasn't even ours.
- Shh.

19:51.713 --> 19:54.341
<i>[ Man On Radio, Indistinct ]</i>
What're you listening to?

19:54.416 --> 19:57.442
Best damn team in America.
Fakes a handoff. He rolls right!

19:57.519 --> 20:01.478
Redskins!
Uh-oh. He's nearly hit at the seven.
He looks. He throws--

20:01.556 --> 20:05.617
Touchdown, Redskins!

20:05.694 --> 20:09.289
I love it
when they beat the Cowboys.

20:09.364 --> 20:11.161
Go, Redskins!

20:11.233 --> 20:13.633
Go, Redskins!

20:13.702 --> 20:16.933
<i>[Joseph Chuckling ]</i>
<i>Yah!</i>
<i>[ Sam] Yah!</i>

20:22.444 --> 20:25.641
<i>[ Suzanne ]</i>
Kenu, <i>can you hear me? Over.</i>

20:25.714 --> 20:27.648
Suzanne.

20:27.716 --> 20:29.707
George, you've got to
bring him back.

20:29.785 --> 20:33.221
I can't. We'll go to jail.
[ Suzanne ]
Whose fault is that?

20:33.288 --> 20:37.384
You shouldn't have
stolen that truck
and taken Grandpa with you!

20:37.459 --> 20:39.450
<i>Kenu,</i> come home.

20:39.528 --> 20:42.986
I don't want you to die out there.
I want you to be at my wedding.

20:46.368 --> 20:48.302
You're getting married?

20:48.370 --> 20:52.966
No, no, no. I-- I just want you
to be here if I do.

20:53.041 --> 20:55.271
For the future.

20:55.344 --> 20:58.836
Turn yourself in, George.
I'll recommend
the judge to go easy on ya.

20:58.914 --> 21:01.314
<i>Kenu,</i> listen to him.

21:02.651 --> 21:06.314
When was the last time
a white man kept his word to us?

21:06.388 --> 21:09.824
Didn't you learn anything
in that college you went to?

21:09.891 --> 21:13.918
No! I will not come back
and die like a worm...

21:13.996 --> 21:16.396
in some white man's hut.

21:16.465 --> 21:20.765
No, no, no, no!
[ Coughing ]
<i>[ Train Whistle Blowing ]</i>

21:20.836 --> 21:23.566
[ Coughing Continues ]

21:26.308 --> 21:28.242
George!

21:28.310 --> 21:31.575
Damn it.
Hazlitt, go to our alternate channel!

21:31.646 --> 21:33.580
Yes, sir.

21:34.916 --> 21:37.908
- Sheriff, you there?
- Where would the noon freight be by now?

21:37.986 --> 21:40.511
Somewhere around Yellow Springs.
Yeah, that's what I thought.

21:40.589 --> 21:44.252
I'm on my way.
And keep that damned Indian
off the radio!

21:44.326 --> 21:48.422
Call Sheriff Baldwin back
at Buffalo Run and tell him to send
his boys up here on the double.

21:48.497 --> 21:52.866
If they get past Yellow Springs,
we're gonna have a hell of a time
trackin' 'em down.

21:56.138 --> 21:58.572
Does this road
go over the mountains?

21:58.640 --> 22:00.574
No.

22:02.344 --> 22:04.608
Then I don't know
how we're gonna make it.

22:04.679 --> 22:06.613
[Joseph ]
I do! Pull over.

22:09.351 --> 22:11.216
<i>[ Horse Neighs ]</i>

22:12.788 --> 22:15.222
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>Windwalker.</i>

22:16.792 --> 22:18.987
We go home together.

22:27.035 --> 22:29.731
''We will return your horses
as soon as we can.

22:29.805 --> 22:31.739
''They're in good hands.

22:31.807 --> 22:35.072
''P.S. We're not stealin' 'em.
We're only borrowin' 'em.

22:35.143 --> 22:37.771
Please feel free to use our truck.''

22:37.846 --> 22:40.906
It's a stolen truck!
They can't trade it for somethin' else!

22:40.982 --> 22:42.916
And now they've stolen
two horses.

22:42.984 --> 22:45.111
My God,
if it's not one thing,
it's another.

22:45.187 --> 22:47.121
What are they gonna
steal next?

22:47.189 --> 22:50.056
You're lucky
you've got your barn left.

22:50.125 --> 22:52.650
Hazlitt, they've dumped the truck
and taken two horses.

22:52.727 --> 22:56.219
<i>Up into the mountains near Tyrol Pass.</i>
<i>I'm goin'after 'em.</i>

22:56.298 --> 22:58.323
Tyrol Pass.

23:04.739 --> 23:06.673
[Joseph ]
Whoa.

23:10.812 --> 23:12.746
You all right?

23:20.021 --> 23:21.989
Didn't you leave anything
in the store?

23:22.057 --> 23:24.457
Not if I could help it.

23:27.762 --> 23:30.629
Here. You open it.

23:31.633 --> 23:33.828
<i>[ Neighs ]</i>

23:39.241 --> 23:43.803
<i>[ Al ]</i>
<i>This is terrific, Sam.</i>
<i>He's painting society marks on.</i>

23:43.879 --> 23:46.143
You're part of
a Shoshone war party.

23:46.214 --> 23:49.479
I don't wanna be on the warpath.
I wanna get him some medical help.

23:49.551 --> 23:51.815
How's that paint coming?
<i>It's ready.</i>

23:57.492 --> 23:59.892
<i>[ Hawk Screeches ]</i>

23:59.961 --> 24:04.864
When I was in World War I,
only the officers had ponies.

24:04.933 --> 24:07.629
I could never get over...

24:07.702 --> 24:10.671
how naked they look
without their markings.

24:10.739 --> 24:14.004
<i>How could you tell</i>
<i>what they had done?</i>

24:14.075 --> 24:16.600
<i>How could you</i>
<i>frighten your enemies?</i>

24:17.946 --> 24:20.039
It made no sense to me.

24:26.188 --> 24:30.181
Here. You stole the horses too.

24:35.363 --> 24:39.766
<i>[ Al ]</i>
<i>Sam, this is just terrific.</i>
<i>It's like the past come to life.</i>

24:39.834 --> 24:42.962
You know, he just--
he painted the hoof prints on there.

24:43.038 --> 24:45.404
And that's to show how many
horse raids they went on,

24:45.473 --> 24:47.464
or how many horses they stole.

24:48.810 --> 24:53.770
- I thought we just borrowed 'em.
- The horses don't know that, eh?

24:53.848 --> 24:56.817
[ Chuckles ]
That's a good one.
<i>[Joseph Chuckling ]</i>

25:02.891 --> 25:04.825
Ah.

25:15.904 --> 25:19.863
- What are the handprints for?
- For men killed in battle.

25:29.451 --> 25:32.249
- Go on.
- Uh, well, I, uh--

25:32.320 --> 25:34.254
Go on, <i>Togo.</i>

25:35.724 --> 25:37.658
I can see it in your eyes.

26:06.121 --> 26:08.612
Now we are ready.

26:12.861 --> 26:17.889
<i>Sam, Ziggy did</i>
<i>a topographical analysis.</i>
<i>He says that's the best way to go.</i>

26:17.966 --> 26:20.867
I'm worried about him, Al.
<i>He looks all right to me.</i>

26:22.337 --> 26:26.706
- You're not a doctor.
- Hey, don't count the old boy out.
He might outlive you.

26:26.775 --> 26:29.300
- <i>[ Gunshot ]</i>
- [ Groans ]

26:29.377 --> 26:31.572
- Sam!
- <i>Togo!</i>

26:34.316 --> 26:36.250
[ Taggart ]
George, can you hear me?

26:39.788 --> 26:42.018
Damn.

26:42.090 --> 26:44.024
Maybe I need glasses after all.

26:44.092 --> 26:47.084
Where'd you get the rifle?

26:47.162 --> 26:49.357
Traded for it!

26:49.431 --> 26:52.298
[ Groans ]
Sam, are you okay?
Where'd you get hit?

26:52.367 --> 26:54.699
Yeah, I think it got me
in the ribs.

26:59.741 --> 27:04.041
Sam. Ah, you're lucky, Sam.
It just took a little skin,
maybe a little hunk of meat.

27:04.112 --> 27:06.171
It burns like hell.
That's good.

27:06.247 --> 27:08.681
Lets you know you're alive.

27:08.750 --> 27:11.548
[ Gunshot ]

27:11.619 --> 27:13.814
Listen, we gotta try
and get out of here...

27:13.888 --> 27:16.413
before it gets dark
and he traps us up here.

27:16.491 --> 27:19.187
Okay, Grandfather?
<i>Kenu.</i>

27:19.260 --> 27:21.194
<i>Kenu.</i>

27:21.262 --> 27:23.196
Give me--
Give me a second.

27:59.467 --> 28:01.765
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>Hey,you shoot like a white man.</i>

28:01.836 --> 28:03.770
Damn it!

28:54.856 --> 28:57.950
[ Panting ]

29:01.162 --> 29:03.096
Let's just rest here
for a second.

29:03.164 --> 29:06.327
[ Wheezing ]

29:06.401 --> 29:11.964
[ Sighs ]
That was tougher
than a two-dollar whore.

29:12.040 --> 29:16.033
[ Both Chuckling ]

29:16.110 --> 29:19.705
[ Coughing, Wheezing ]

29:25.053 --> 29:26.987
That looks like a cave up there.

29:29.557 --> 29:31.491
Can you make it?

29:43.705 --> 29:45.639
Let's go.

30:04.759 --> 30:07.159
Come on. Go, go.
[ Kisses ]

30:11.799 --> 30:13.733
<i>I'm not sure</i>
<i>he's gonna make it, Al.</i>

30:13.801 --> 30:16.634
<i>Well, he better make it.</i>
<i>Or else you're not gonna</i>
<i>leap out ofhere.</i>

30:16.704 --> 30:19.867
You're gonna leap right into jail.
<i>¿Comprende?</i>

30:19.941 --> 30:21.875
Togo,

30:21.943 --> 30:25.401
there are voices
in the night, eh?

30:25.480 --> 30:29.109
Uh, yeah.

30:29.183 --> 30:32.016
<i>[ Coughing ]</i>

30:43.364 --> 30:45.457
We need a fire.

30:47.001 --> 30:49.265
Won't they see the light?
Or the smoke?

30:49.337 --> 30:54.297
Not if we make it small,
and towards the back.

30:56.377 --> 30:58.311
I'll go get some wood.

30:59.581 --> 31:01.515
Hmm.

31:28.710 --> 31:30.678
What?
Matches.

31:30.745 --> 31:34.306
Matches?
Sam, don't tell me--

31:34.382 --> 31:36.850
I don't have any matches.

31:36.918 --> 31:39.751
Here. I'll show you
an old Indian trick.

31:40.989 --> 31:46.825
(music) [ Chanting ]

31:47.895 --> 31:49.829
<i>Sam, this is great!</i>

31:49.897 --> 31:53.833
(music) [ Continues ]
We're gettin' to watch a bit
of authentic Western history here!

32:02.076 --> 32:03.839
Voilà.

32:12.220 --> 32:14.745
Old Indian trick, huh?

32:14.822 --> 32:19.350
Your dad used to
fall for it every time.

32:25.767 --> 32:27.564
You miss him,
don't you?

32:29.637 --> 32:31.571
Yeah, I guess I do.

32:31.639 --> 32:34.574
Don't you think
you'll ever see him again?

32:38.079 --> 32:40.309
No, I don't think so.

32:41.315 --> 32:43.579
No wonder you want me
to go on living.

32:48.790 --> 32:50.724
Death...

32:50.792 --> 32:52.817
is a doorway.

32:52.894 --> 32:56.022
And we are like the grasshopper.

32:59.434 --> 33:03.803
<i>When we die,</i>
<i>we shed one skin...</i>

33:03.871 --> 33:05.805
and put on another.

33:07.108 --> 33:11.101
And leap to a new life...

33:11.179 --> 33:14.706
<i>on the other side of the door.</i>
What if there's nothing
beyond the door?

33:14.782 --> 33:18.115
Then I would fight
to hang on to this skin...

33:18.186 --> 33:20.120
as hard as I could.

33:21.522 --> 33:23.717
Because it would be all I had.

33:27.228 --> 33:29.162
But it's not.

33:30.231 --> 33:33.029
All of life...

33:33.101 --> 33:35.467
is a series of leaps...

33:35.536 --> 33:37.470
for us grasshoppers.

33:37.538 --> 33:40.974
<i>Eh?</i>
I guess you could say so.

33:41.042 --> 33:44.773
Sometimes we see
where we are going.

33:46.447 --> 33:49.575
Sometimes we don't.

33:51.219 --> 33:53.983
Have you ever leaped...

33:54.055 --> 33:56.285
and not at least survived?

33:56.357 --> 33:58.621
No.

33:59.694 --> 34:02.254
The next time you leap,

34:02.330 --> 34:04.264
remember that.

34:04.332 --> 34:07.768
Is he talking to George,
or is he talking to you, Sam?

34:07.835 --> 34:11.771
And stop trying
to make me hang on...

34:11.839 --> 34:13.773
to my old skin.

34:13.841 --> 34:16.139
<i>Okay?</i>
Okay.

34:16.210 --> 34:18.143
Now,

34:19.246 --> 34:21.943
if we only had some hot dogs.

34:22.016 --> 34:25.975
[ Laughs ]

34:32.592 --> 34:34.527
<i>[ Man On Radio, Indistinct ]</i>

34:36.130 --> 34:38.063
[ Gun Cocks ]

34:42.402 --> 34:46.168
Freeze!
This is J.J.James
on KNFC, 560.

34:46.239 --> 34:48.731
Yah. Yah. Yah. Yah.

34:48.810 --> 34:51.176
<i>[ Horse Neighs ]</i>
[James ]
...yesterday in a fierce competition.

34:55.783 --> 34:57.717
Damn it to hell.

35:09.931 --> 35:13.162
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>Once we roamed from the deserts</i>
<i>to the mountains.</i>

35:14.368 --> 35:17.895
<i>Before the white man.</i>
<i>Now there are fewer of us.</i>

35:17.972 --> 35:19.940
And fewer memories...

35:20.007 --> 35:21.941
of what we once were.

35:22.009 --> 35:24.534
That's all the more reason
for you to stay alive,

35:24.612 --> 35:26.546
to fight to stay alive.

35:26.614 --> 35:28.946
<i>So that you can pass on</i>
<i>those memories.</i>

35:29.016 --> 35:32.349
No one wants to remember them.

35:32.420 --> 35:34.411
They have no heart for it.

35:35.756 --> 35:38.247
They are ashamed of what they are.

35:39.827 --> 35:42.887
They go to the cities
and take jobs in factories.

35:42.964 --> 35:45.865
<i>Or become schoolteachers.</i>

35:45.933 --> 35:48.868
Maybe they're just
searching for something...

35:48.936 --> 35:50.870
for themselves.

35:50.938 --> 35:53.065
They don't know who they are,

35:54.876 --> 35:58.004
because they've forgotten
who they are.

36:00.982 --> 36:04.213
How much further
do we have to go?

36:04.285 --> 36:06.344
That river...

36:06.420 --> 36:09.912
<i>marks the southern border</i>
<i>of the reservation area.</i>

36:09.991 --> 36:11.959
<i>[ Sam ]</i>
<i>And as far as Taggart can go.</i>

36:12.026 --> 36:14.654
Well, let's do it.

36:14.729 --> 36:16.890
[ Sam ]
Hyah!

36:16.964 --> 36:20.229
[Joseph ]
Hyah! [ Chuckling ]

36:20.301 --> 36:23.134
[ Coughing ]

36:25.373 --> 36:27.136
Joseph!

36:31.479 --> 36:34.073
[ Groans ]

36:34.148 --> 36:37.549
Why-- Why did you
let that mule kick me?

36:38.986 --> 36:41.352
Just hold still.

36:41.422 --> 36:43.413
Let me see if anything's broken.

36:49.063 --> 36:51.554
Ow. Ooh.

36:51.632 --> 36:54.226
[ Sighs ]

36:54.302 --> 36:56.736
Yeah, there's a break right there.

36:57.772 --> 37:00.332
[ Groans ]

37:09.016 --> 37:10.950
[Joseph ]
My father used to tell me tales...

37:11.018 --> 37:13.543
of being chased by the soldiers...

37:13.621 --> 37:16.556
in the Plains Wars of the 1 87 0s.

37:16.624 --> 37:18.558
I used to envy him.

37:18.626 --> 37:20.560
Now...
[ Coughs ]

37:20.628 --> 37:22.562
I'm not so sure.

37:22.630 --> 37:24.564
It's just a little further.

37:24.632 --> 37:27.465
So's New York.
[ Groans ]

37:27.535 --> 37:29.662
<i>Kenu,</i> when we get
to the reservation--

37:29.737 --> 37:32.262
to the reservation--
No! No, Marcus Welby.

37:34.141 --> 37:36.336
[ Coughing, Wheezing ]

37:36.410 --> 37:38.344
But there's so much
I don't know,

37:38.412 --> 37:42.508
that I can learn from you,
that-- that others can learn too.

37:42.583 --> 37:46.110
There's only one thing
you have to learn:

37:46.187 --> 37:48.121
that freedom...

37:48.189 --> 37:51.750
is the greatest gift
we're born with,

37:52.860 --> 37:56.193
and the hardest thing
to hold on to.

38:02.636 --> 38:06.128
The world is like
a giant spider, <i>Togo,</i>

38:06.207 --> 38:08.175
spinnin' its web.

38:08.242 --> 38:10.733
Each strand
we could easily break.

38:10.811 --> 38:13.405
But if we let them
wrap around us,

38:13.481 --> 38:17.679
suddenly you are no longer free,
but food for the spiders, eh?

38:17.752 --> 38:20.243
<i>[ Horse Neighing ]</i>

38:21.589 --> 38:23.523
<i>Kenu!</i>

38:24.592 --> 38:27.117
It's gonna take
a whole passel of husbands...

38:27.194 --> 38:29.594
to handle a woman that stubborn.

38:32.199 --> 38:35.930
You should have never taken him
from the nursing home.
Everything was fine there.

38:36.003 --> 38:38.369
- Not for him.
- Well, how would you know?

38:38.439 --> 38:40.771
You haven't been around
for 1 0 years.

38:40.841 --> 38:43.332
Maybe I haven't.

38:43.411 --> 38:46.642
But I've come to realize that--
<i>I didn't want to put him</i>
<i>in a state home.</i>

38:46.714 --> 38:51.151
But even with the money you sent,
we couldn't afford a private one.
My apartment is too small.

38:51.218 --> 38:53.846
<i>And who's gonna take care ofhim</i>
<i>during the day when I work?</i>

38:53.921 --> 38:57.652
- <i>[ Sam ] He takes good care ofhimself.</i>
- His emphysema's getting worse each day.

38:57.725 --> 39:00.023
<i>How long will he be able</i>
<i>to do that?</i>

39:00.094 --> 39:03.257
I think that's the point.

39:07.201 --> 39:09.761
No wonder we lost
to the white man.

39:09.837 --> 39:12.670
While you two were fighting,
the sheriff came over the ridge.

39:12.740 --> 39:15.470
- Get <i>Kenu</i> across the river.
- George--

39:15.543 --> 39:17.306
I'll be okay.

39:17.378 --> 39:19.505
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>George,</i>

39:19.580 --> 39:21.241
are you going to scalp him?

39:21.315 --> 39:23.249
No.

39:24.618 --> 39:26.882
Oh, too bad.

39:28.122 --> 39:32.923
If ever a man deserved scalping,
he does.

39:39.667 --> 39:41.965
Joseph!

39:42.036 --> 39:44.197
<i>[ Gun Cocks ]</i>

39:45.106 --> 39:47.267
[ Gun Fires ]

39:50.077 --> 39:53.513
[ Both Groaning ]

40:01.388 --> 40:04.380
[ Groaning Continues ]

40:29.416 --> 40:32.385
Sam!
Don't do it!

40:32.453 --> 40:34.944
You've already got him!

40:41.562 --> 40:44.827
I thought you were really
gonna scalp him.

40:44.899 --> 40:46.833
I was.

40:51.071 --> 40:53.039
<i>[Joseph ]</i>
<i>Yah!</i>
No!

40:53.107 --> 40:55.268
[ Groans ]

40:55.342 --> 40:57.537
<i>Kenu!</i>

40:59.313 --> 41:01.247
<i>Kenu.</i>

41:02.816 --> 41:05.046
Did you scalp him?

41:05.119 --> 41:07.349
<i>Kenu.</i>

41:07.421 --> 41:09.912
No.

41:09.990 --> 41:11.924
I gave him
a haircut instead.

41:16.197 --> 41:19.257
<i>In the movies,</i>
<i>it would've hit my lighter,</i>

41:20.401 --> 41:22.335
and I'd be okay.

41:24.572 --> 41:27.132
Maybe next time.

41:35.349 --> 41:37.476
There is nothing worse...

41:37.551 --> 41:40.111
than warm water.

41:44.024 --> 41:45.958
You like football?

41:46.026 --> 41:50.429
I, uh, don't watch it
that much, Grandfather.

41:50.497 --> 41:53.227
You should.

41:53.300 --> 41:58.761
'Cause the Redskins are
the best damn team in America.

41:58.839 --> 42:01.808
<i>[ Coughs ]</i>

42:04.211 --> 42:06.111
Looks like rain.

42:09.883 --> 42:11.748
Did we make it?

42:13.754 --> 42:15.688
Not yet.

42:15.756 --> 42:17.690
Help me get him up.

42:27.568 --> 42:29.502
[ Sam Grunts ]

42:31.739 --> 42:34.674
George!

42:34.742 --> 42:36.801
You cross the river
and I'll shoot!

42:36.877 --> 42:39.505
All he wanted to do
was to die in peace,

42:42.349 --> 42:44.977
to die the way he wanted to.

42:45.052 --> 42:47.384
<i>He didn't wanna die</i>
<i>inside of a building,</i>

42:47.454 --> 42:50.218
surrounded by people
he didn't know,
hooked up to machines.

42:54.161 --> 42:56.686
He wanted to die
surrounded by his friends.

42:59.700 --> 43:03.636
By the sky.
By the wind.

43:03.704 --> 43:07.470
By the open spaces
that he grew up with.

43:07.541 --> 43:09.475
They were his family.

43:11.545 --> 43:13.479
They were his friends.

43:18.585 --> 43:21.213
All he wanted to do was...

43:21.288 --> 43:23.222
die with dignity.

43:28.162 --> 43:31.063
George!
[ Gun Cocks ]

43:39.673 --> 43:41.607
[ Uncocks Gun ]

43:43.377 --> 43:46.471
Hang on, <i>Kenu.</i>
Hang on.

43:50.084 --> 43:53.076
Why are you crying, <i>Togo?</i>

43:53.153 --> 43:55.087
I don't know.

43:58.292 --> 44:00.658
Do you like the Redskins?

44:05.065 --> 44:06.999
Best damn team in America.

44:10.437 --> 44:12.769
Don't cry, <i>Togo.</i>

44:12.840 --> 44:14.808
You're a good boy.

44:14.875 --> 44:17.776
I'll tell your father
when I see him.

44:19.413 --> 44:21.711
[ Coughs ]
It's just a little further, <i>Kenu.</i>

44:22.716 --> 44:24.650
Just a...

44:28.822 --> 44:30.949
We made it.
[ Grunts ]

